### Common Collections in Rust

Rust's standard library provides several collection types beyond basic arrays and vectors. This topic covers the full range of collection utilities.

---

### Collection Overview

| Type | Description |
|------|-------------|
| `Vec<T>` | Growable array |
| `VecDeque<T>` | Double-ended queue |
| `LinkedList<T>` | Doubly-linked list |
| `HashMap<K, V>` | Key-value map with hash |
| `HashSet<T>` | Set with hash |
| `BTreeMap<K, V>` | Sorted key-value map |
| `BTreeSet<T>` | Sorted set |
| `BinaryHeap<T>` | Max-heap priority queue |

---

### Choosing the Right Collection

```rust
use std::collections::*;

// VecDeque - efficient push/pop at both ends
let mut deque = VecDeque::new();
deque.push_back(1);
deque.push_front(2);

// BinaryHeap - max-heap
let mut heap = BinaryHeap::new();
heap.push(5);
heap.push(1);
heap.push(10);
assert_eq!(heap.pop(), Some(10));  // largest first

// BTreeMap - sorted keys
let mut map = BTreeMap::new();
map.insert(3, "three");
map.insert(1, "one");
map.insert(2, "two");
// Iterates in key order: 1, 2, 3

// BTreeSet - sorted set
let mut set = BTreeSet::new();
set.insert(3);
set.insert(1);
set.insert(2);
// Iterates in order: 1, 2, 3
```

> **Key Point:** The standard library collections cover most use cases. Use `VecDeque` for FIFO/LIFO queues, `BTreeMap` when you need sorted iteration, `BinaryHeap` for priority queue behavior, and `HashMap`/`HashSet` for hash-based lookup.

codeExample:
use std::collections::{BinaryHeap, VecDeque, BTreeMap};

fn main() {
    // VecDeque as queue
    let mut queue = VecDeque::new();
    queue.push_back("first");
    queue.push_back("second");
    queue.push_back("third");
    println!("Queue front: {:?}", queue.pop_front());

    // BinaryHeap as priority queue
    let mut heap = BinaryHeap::new();
    heap.push(3);
    heap.push(1);
    heap.push(5);
    println!("Max: {:?}", heap.pop());

    // BTreeMap maintains sorted order
    let mut scores = BTreeMap::new();
    scores.insert("Charlie", 85);
    scores.insert("Alice", 92);
    scores.insert("Bob", 78);
    println!("Sorted scores: {:?}", scores);
}
